<text>I keep getting asked to leave a review so here it goes. I went to NEXT Dentistry for TMJ after struggling for three years to figure out why I was in pain. I had a creepy feeling about this place from the beginning but I was desperate for pain relief. I faithfully followed Dr. Hemingway's method for nine months and was not significantly relieved. Then I started to just go ahead and wean off the device anyway and was feeling better. However, I was not back to the same pain-free life I had almost four years prior. I started seeing a physical therapist for TMJ and he suggested just trying an over the counter mouth guard and it saved my life. For about three weeks now, I've even been wearing this DenTek guard during the day, thanks to covid and working from home. I finally feel like myself again!

I went in for a final follow up with Dr. Hemingway and when I told him what I've been doing I got "well of course the squishy, flexible guard is going to feel better."

I'm sad $15,000 went to Dr. Hemingway instead of taking care of my family. Furthermore, Dr. Hemingway was never up front about how much this would cost. After each phase, he'd tell me the price of the next step and, not having any other answers for my pain, it felt like I had to finish what I started.

I feel very manipulated by this place.

One piece of advice, if anyone from the office reads this: the surveys that a patient fills out at each visit should have them assess how they have felt in the past week or so. Having a survey ask how they feel in that moment is not very accurate because sometimes I had better days than other days.<//text><date>1597637734254< /date>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

I had my appointment today. PETRA greeted me at the door and after taking my temperature, to be sure I was COVID free, escorted me back to her area for my cleaning. Dawn Rinehart</user_name>
<user>112899821835208504975</user>< Review>
My family was referred to NextDentistry by a friend.  My husband became a client before me.  He knew I had some anxiety issues regarding dentists, but he assured me I would love Dr. Hemingway and his staff.  Due to a broken molar, and other issues,  I made my appointment.  I was very nervous, and the staff tried to reassure me upon my arrival to complete my paperwork.  When I got into my room, my medical history was reviewed, and my blood pressure was taken.  My pressure was very high.  I was told about all the risks of high blood pressure (remember, this is a dental practice), and was told that no work could be performed until my pressure was down. The doctor and staff were very concerned about me.   I went straight to my doctor that afternoon, and was given an EKG, which thankfully was normal, and I left with a prescription to bring my pressure down.  I have since had all of my dental work completed, which included crowns, and deep root cleaning.  The state of the art equipment made all procedures pretty easy to handle.  I believe had I not gone to NextDentistry, I would have ignored some very serious health symptoms, and could have ended up very sick.  I  am thankful that my health meant more to them than me on my first meeting with the NextDentistry team.  I highly recommend NextDentistry, and can attest that no other dental office will care about your dental health, and your overall well being more than Dr. Hemingway and his team.  Excellent experience from the moment you walk into the inviting waiting area to when you check out to leave.<//Review>

Currently one of the main Vaccination sites for Covid-19 can be accessed from the 7th floor of the parking structure. Easy access and easy FREE parking for Covid vaccinations. WARNING: FREE PARKING for Covid is ONLY at 5-6-7 Floors of the parking structure, which is NOT accessible from the main entrance (Currently blocked before 5th floor). You should turn at the STOP sign Voigt & Hopkins and take the side entrance at 6th floor. Around 25 vaccination stations guarantee quick and safe roll of the appointments. Mostly under the sun you may need some water with you. Be prepared for very, very long lines over an hour and a half (April 19) !</review>

< review>
Apart from the increased cost of parking here for a full day ($16, up from $8 about a year ago), this structure suits your basic parking needs. There's pay stations on each floor and an elevator & stairs on each end: NorthWest & SouthEast.

Beware when parking during the school year: if you're not in a spot by 9:45AM, then you'll be circling around for an hour hoping that you'll find those blessed white back-up lights as someone is on their way out.</review>

<rating>1</rating><Text>This place is usually pretty pleasant and awesome. However, that's not the experience I just had.

I even tried to start things by saying "hi". heard me, but still looked up and away from me as I was standing there. I then had to ask, "can you help me?" and his response was a lazy "eh".

So, I didn't understand why this became so difficult but, I just started to ask if he could show me what they had in universal vape cartridges and he straight up said "no". I replied "excuse me?" and he said nothing. So, as I had to continually press him for help, he just stood there and didn't answer any of my questions. He was more interested in talking to other people in the shop, than help me for a damn minute. I then just pointed at what I wanted out of the 2 cartridges for $45, and he said they don't do that. I then had to point out the sign for him that advertised that and he still didn't believe me and grabbed the iPad to check. I was right, it's listed clearly.

He packed me a half an 8th of the OG and not 1/4 that I originally asked for, but by that time, I was just so over dealing with him and being in there that I wanted to be done. I paid, I tipped, and I left.

<date>1546389618447<//date><Rating>5<//Rating><review>Another hidden gem in the East Bay. Located near the Oakland airport, this nature preserve offers great viewing of migratory birds , as well as yearly residents. If you are lucky, you might even spot a Ridgway's rail! The pathways are all tarmac, so it is great for folks with mobility issues. <Text>Great walk on the north shore. Entrance close to Harley Davidson dealership. Canal to bridge. Your choice to go left or right. South side is a larger park area. North side continues for about 3 miles from starting point. <Text>Love this walk! The trail is well maintained . We bring bags to pick up trash that unconscious people leave. <gmapID>0x808f85b9c3e256ff:0x6a0884be78b8bc82< /gmapID>< review>
Plenty of easy access parking, alongside the estuary. You can watch kayaking and canoeing from a comfortable grassy area, equipped with a picnic table and a grill for cooking burgers, chicken and franks, and more. Be sure to use an actual address as there are many entrances. The one described in this review is 7250 Doolittle, in Oakland.</review>

< review>
I commute through here several times a week, generally about 7 AM, 9PM,  or 1AM (depends on my work shift). I see skunks, egrets, blue herons, ground squirrels, fairy rings, Kingfishers, mushrooms; and, rarely, owls, otters, and sharks. So, I love it!< /review>

<rate>5</rate>< review>
I work nearby so steal an hour when I can to go out for a walk here n the coast line. It provides the perfect scenery for a little escape from work and blasting air conditioning to visit the variety of critters (squirrels, bunnies and lizards) as well as a myriad of birds. It's very quiet and clean and well maintained. I bring my kids here to ride bikes along the miles and miles on paved pathway when I have time as well. Nice place. I'm here at least 4 days a week.< /review>

<Name>Nancy Mason</Name><date>1552924700135<//date><Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
We come here often. It‚Äôs a great place to walk and always loaded with birds. A spotting scope is helpful to really see all the birds in the distance on the water. But there are plenty of birds up close. Look for burrowing owls on the mounds as you drive in. You may hear or see ridgeways rails out in the master as well.</Review>

1545191625305</time>
< rating>
5<//rating>
<Text>The Martin Luther King Jr. Regional Shoreline park is, in my opinion, a hidden gem for the City of Oakland.

Did you know that there is a multi-use path (bicycles and pedestrians) that winds for 3.7 miles along the shoreline with any interrupting roads? Even my home city of Richmond, with the longest completed sections of the San Francisco Bay Trail of ANY city around the bay can't claim that long an uninterrupted shoreline trail!

And it's empty!! Are you tired of the Bay Trail in Emeryville through Richmond? Yes, that section is lovely, but that section is also CROWDED.

I enthusiastically recommend this park if you like to walk or bike along the shore, with wildlife viewing, interpretive displays, and most of all - peace and uncrowded quiet - all within the City of Oakland!< /Text>< pictures>
None</pictures>

<text>Great place to take a walk, see lots of shorebirds and other wildlife (squirrels, rabbits, I even saw a red fox once), or to have a picnic. Thanks to the EBRP, Audubon Society, Save the Bay, and other organizations for restoration and cleanup efforts, the park, Arrowhead marsh, and the shoreline is kept in really good shape considering it's located in the middle of Oakland. The main drawback is all the trash that floats down and accumulates after a rain storm. All the more reason to thank the people and organizations that do regular shoreline cleanup.</text>< name>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
Awesome place for bird watching! There are many species that can be spotted here if you're into that. Also a great place to watch the Angels fly practice runs when they're in the SF Bay Area.
It's a flat park that stretches along the estuary and is used by many of the local businesses for daytime exercise. There are picnic areas, restrooms and a play area for ppl and dogs.
Many ppl fish along the shores as well.<//review>

<userid>104140437281161871703</userid>< user_name>
Kristen mariposa</user_name>
< Date>
1618106276058< /Date>
<rate>4<//rate>< Text>
UPDATE 2021: The bathrooms are seriously boarded up. Was locking the door not sufficient?

2019: Beautiful. Nice place to walk your dog. This trail is a stretch of several shoreline trails that loop around the channel.  You can see it on the ebparks website.
Ample parking in several lots around the park.
There are lots of picnic table areas with grills, many with water fountains.  Many restrooms both single room and stalls.  Viewing Dock that goes out into the marsh. Great area for wildlife photography. A sandbox for kids.  Across the water there is a boat ramp if you want to take your boat out.
There is also a stocked doggy waste bag station in the parking lot where the boat ramp is located. . Throughout the park there are dog waste bag stations stocked by the community.
At the Doolittle Dr entrance there is also a community venue available for rental for weddings, birthdays etc. You can pick up a flyer with rates and other info outside in a box attached to the building. Im sure info is also available on the ebparks website.< /Text>

<user>110102783699908715373</user>< Name>
Thomas Finch</Name>
< time>
1528638921381<//time>
< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< review>
I absolutely live this park. I can't believe it took us a year to find it! We always park at the 66th street terminal by 580, but there are five entrances total.
The birds here are fantastic.  You can see egrets, owls, flickers, coots, quails, all sorts if rails, sanspipers, willets, yellowlegs, etc, terns, what must be a dozen kinds of gulls, ocean going ducks, plain ol' mallard ducks, sparrows, songbirds, and of course pigeons, including both feral domestics and rock doves.
And you can see all of this while walking a gentle out and back trail that crosses several times over little creeks as it stretches around the marshy shoreline from 66th street to the Oakland airport and almost to Alameda. It's a great time.<//review>
<Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None<//response><gmap_id>0x808f85b9c3e256ff:0x6a0884be78b8bc82< /gmap_id></record>

<Date>1528638921381<//Date>< Review>
I absolutely live this park. I can't believe it took us a year to find it! We always park at the 66th street terminal by 580, but there are five entrances total.
The birds here are fantastic.  You can see egrets, owls, flickers, coots, quails, all sorts if rails, sanspipers, willets, yellowlegs, etc, terns, what must be a dozen kinds of gulls, ocean going ducks, plain ol' mallard ducks, sparrows, songbirds, and of course pigeons, including both feral domestics and rock doves.
And you can see all of this while walking a gentle out and back trail that crosses several times over little creeks as it stretches around the marshy shoreline from 66th street to the Oakland airport and almost to Alameda. It's a great time.</Review>
